TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Stigma of Bankruptcy: Spoiled Organizational Image and Its Management
AU  - Sutton, Robert I.
AU  - Callahan, Anita L.
Y1  - 1987/09/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256007
DO  - 10.5465/256007
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 405
EP  - 436
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Interview, archival, and observational data from four computer firms were used to develop a theory about how Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code spoils the image of top managers and firms. We propose that Chapter 11 is a discrediting label that causes key organizational audiences to have negative reactions towards a firm, including disengagement, reduction in the quality of participation, bargaining for more favorable exchange relationships, and denigrating an organization and its leaders. Those negative reactions further increase the probability of organizational death and threaten managerial careers. We also propose a hierarchy of stigma-management strategies that leaders may use in their efforts to avert or repair the spoiled images of top management and firms.
AB  - Interview, archival, and observational data from four computer firms were used to develop a theory about how Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code spoils the image of top managers and firms. We propose that Chapter 11 is a discrediting label that causes key organizational audiences to have negative reactions towards a firm, including disengagement, reduction in the quality of participation, bargaining for more favorable exchange relationships, and denigrating an organization and its leaders. Those negative reactions further increase the probability of organizational death and threaten managerial careers. We also propose a hierarchy of stigma-management strategies that leaders may use in their efforts to avert or repair the spoiled images of top management and firms.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256007
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256007
Y2  - 2026/04/24
